# Shader Creation Rules

1. Edit `index.html`. Add the shader source as a new entry in the `S` object
   (template-string GLSL), and add a registry entry to the `userShaders` array
   at the top of the registry section. Give it a unique snake_case id, a
   human-readable name, and a short description.

2. The shader MUST be a WebGL2 GLSL ES 3.00 fragment shader with this exact
   interface:
     #version 300 es
     precision highp float;
     out vec4 fragColor;
     uniform vec2 u_res;   // canvas resolution in pixels
     uniform float u_time; // elapsed time in seconds

3. Use ONLY u_res and u_time as inputs. No textures, no additional uniforms,
   no mouse input.

4. The shader must produce interesting, smoothly animated visuals. Aim for
   something that looks good as a screensaver or ambient display.

5. Write all math/noise functions inline — don't rely on external libraries.
   Common building blocks: simplex/value noise, fbm, domain warping,
   raymarching, SDFs.

6. Keep the shader self-contained in one fragment shader string. It should
   compile and run without errors.

7. Do NOT copy an existing shader from the gallery. Create something original
   that matches the user's idea.
